{"id":"exploring-magnets-6","label":"Exploring Magnets","lockAfter":2,"list":[{"id":"notes","type":"passage","label":"Notes","data":{"title":"Exploring Magnets","text":"In olden days, sailors used naturally occurring magnets, also known as lodestone to find direction in the sea. Later on, people found out that magnets could also be made from pieces of iron. Nowadays, we have magnets made of different materials.\nMost of the magnets present in the household things are artificial magnets. Magnets come in different shapes: Bar magnet, U-shaped magnet, ring magnet. \nMaterials that are attracted by the magnet are called magnetic materials. eg: iron, nickel, cobalt\nMaterials that are not attracted by the magnet are called non-magnetic materials. eg: paper, cloth, plastic, glass\n# Poles of Magnet\nTake some iron filings on a sheet of paper. They are nothing but very small pieces of iron. If you move a bar magnet near to them, the iron filings stick to the magnet. You can observe that maximum iron filings stick near the ends of the bar magnet. These ends of the magnet are called the two poles of the magnet - the north pole and south pole. These two poles are present in magnets of all shapes.\nIf we break a magnet into smaller pieces, each piece will have a north and south pole. It is not possible to obtain a magnet with a single pole. \n# Finding direction\nA freely suspended magnet comes to rest along the north-south direction. The end of the magnet that points towards north direction is called the North-seeking pole or the North pole of the magnet. The other end that points towards the South direction is called the South-seeking pole or the South pole of the magnet. It is because our Earth itself behaves like a giant magnet.\nThe property of a freely suspended magnet to always rest along the north-south direction is used to find directions. Based on this, a small device called a magnetic compass was developed in olden days for finding directions. It has a magnet in the shape of a needle which can rotate freely. The needle of a magnetic compass indicates the north-south direction.\nWe can make our own magnet, by rubbing the two ends of a magnet against the two ends of an iron needle.\nWe can make our own magnetic compass, by inserting a magnetic needle in a cork horizontally, and making it float on a bowl of water.\n# A pair of bar magnet.\nMagnets don't only show attractive behaviour, they also show repulsive behaviour. If you bring two north poles of two different magnet together, they repel each other. Like poles attract, unlike poles repel.\nIn some magnets, the North and South poles are marked as N and S. In some other magnets, the North pole is indicated by a white dot. Sometimes, the North pole of a magnet is painted red and South pole is painted blue.\n# Taking care of magnet\nKeep magnets in pair with unlike poles on the same side. Keep as piece of wood in between. Place two pieces of soft iron across the ends. Do not heat, do not throw and drop, do not hammer magnet. Do not keep magnets near mobile phones or remote controls.\n"}},{"label":"Fill in the blanks","type":"matchByDragDrop","id":"fillup","onlyBigScreen":true,"commonData":{"dashWidth":100,"actWidth":1300,"fontSize":"2rem","dashHeight":"2.7rem","labelsOnSide":true},"data":["In olden days, sailors used naturally occurring magnets, also known as *lodestone* to find direction in the sea. \nMost of the artificial magnets are made from *iron*.\nAn example for magnetic material is *nickel*.\nAn example for non magnetic material is *glass*.\nFreely suspended magnet always show the north direction, because of the magnetic behavior of the *Earth*.","If we take two magnets and try to bring them closer, the *unlike poles* attract, and *like poles* repel.\nThe north pole of a magnet is usually painted *red*, and the south pole is painted *blue*. In some magnets, the north pole is represented by a *white* dot.\nA freely *suspended* magnet comes to rest along the north-south direction."]},{"id":"mcq","label":"Multiple Choice Questions","type":"mcq","data":{"questions":[{"qText":"In olden days, how sailors found direction in the night?","options":"From the position of stars\nFrom the position of moon\nThey cannot. They sleep and wait for the sun.\nUsing magnetic compass"},{"qText":"Which of the following is not a type of magnet?","options":"Triangular magnet, Bar magnet, Ring magnet, U-shaped magnet"},{"qText":"Which of the following is a magnetic material?","options":"cobalt, cloth, plastic, glass"},{"qText":"Which of the following statement is false?","options":"Two north poles attract each other.\nUnlike poles attract each other.\nLike poles repel each other.\nBoth north and south pole attract iron filings."},{"qText":"If we move a bar magnet over iron filings, what will happen to the iron filings?","options":"Most of them deposit at the two ends of the magnet.\n            They uniformly deposit on the magnet.\n            Most of them deposit at the center of the magnet.\n            Most of them deposit around the north pole."}]}},{"label":"True or False","id":"true-false","type":"classifySentence","data":{"title":"Classify the below sentences as true and false","types":[{"name":"True","text":"Our Earth itself behave like a big magnet.\nMagnets should be properly protected after using it."},{"name":"False","text":"If we cut a bar magnet at the center, we get two magnets, one having only north pole, and another having only south pole.\nIf we keep a magnet on a table, it automatically turns to the North direction.\nIt is not possible to have a ring magnet."}]}},{"id":"fillup-2","label":"Fill Up","type":"fillup","data":{"text":"If we bring two north poles together, they *repel (attract)* each other.\nIf we bring the south pole of a magnet, near the north pole of another magnet, they *attract (repel)* each other.\nIf we bring two south poles together, they *repel (attract)* each other.\nThe device used to find direction is * magnetic compass (lodestone)*.\nIron filings are *small (large)* pieces of iron.\nMagnetic compass has a *magnetic needle (bar magnet)."}},{"id":"magnet-experiment","type":"slides2","label":"Experimenting with Magnet","data":{"title":"Experimenting with Magnet","displayType":"steps","images":"img/science/big/exploring-magnets-6","imgHeight":400,"fontSize":"1.5rem","steps":[{"text":"Let us take some iron filings and spread it over a paper. If we move a bar magnet close to it, maximum iron filings stick near the ends of the bar magnet.","img":"iron-filings"},{"text":"We can convert a needle into a magnet. Rub the north pole of a magnet from one end of the needle to another end. Repeat it for 40 times. The needle will behave like a magnet.","img":"my-magnet"},{"text":"Pass this needle through a cork horizontally. Float the cork in a glass bowl filled with water. The needle will rotate and align with North-South direction. My own magnetic compass.","img":"my-magnetic-compass"},{"text":"If we bring a bar magnet near a magnetic compass, the needle will deflect based on their polarity. It even deflects, if we place a non magnetic material like wood between them.","img":"field-across-wood"},{"text":"Using the fact that magnetic field is stronger at the poles, and magnetic field can be passed through magnetic materials in contact, we can form a magnetic garland like this.","img":"garland"},{"text":"Create a maze like this using a cardboard tray, straw, and small iron balls. Can you move the iron balls to the exit by moving the magnet below the cardboard?","img":"maze"},{"text":"Can we pick out a steel paper clip fallen in water using a magnet, without getting our fingers or the magnet wet?","img":"across-glass"},{"text":"Will the two cars speed towards each other or run away from each other when brought closer?","img":"matchstick-cars"},{"text":"Protect the magnets properly. For a pair of bar magnet, keep the unlike poles on the same side, and keep a piece of wood in between. Place 2 pieces of soft iron across the ends.","img":"protecting-magnet"}]}}]}